Forgery: see the Introduction, p. 60, no. 22

Described by Conway, pp. 66-7, N. vi, as ‘a small circular altar of marble whose surface had been much broken, standing in the Casa della piccola Fontana’, Reg. V1, 8, 23-24 (see Fiorelli, Pompeianarum Antiquitatum Historia II, 4 (1819-30) (1862) pp. 190-203), but found by neither Rosalba Antonini nor us. We have the gravest doubts whether the object was an altar, rather than the base of a marble basin, whether it was inscribed (Conway: 'I noticed what appeared to be the remains of letters ... but they and still more the remains of what I took to be a line beneath them were too faint to be read with certainty’), and if so whether it was inscribed in Oscan. We deliberately exclude the text, but would not be surprised if it belonged with Pompei 44 (11)
Latin: see M.11. Crawford, “Latin or Greek or Messapic not Italic’ (forthcoming)
